<subSubSection id="C342653D7C11CD2427B79DB2FDF3F931" pageId="23" pageNumber="124" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE736B67C11CD2427B79DB2FDF3F931" blockId="23.[151,1436,1518,1903]" pageId="23" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis id="B92CEAA47C11CD2427B79DB2FEF3F9A1" bold="true" box="[151,273,1518,1543]" pageId="23" pageNumber="124">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
MALE. The following combination of characters is diagnostic for 
<emphasis id="B92CEAA47C11CD24230B9DACFAEFF9A1" box="[1067,1293,1518,1543]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="124">
<taxonomicName id="4C584D357C11CD24230B9DACFAE5F9A1" authorityName="Williams &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2009" box="[1067,1287,1518,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polemomechana">L. polemomechana</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
the body is almost entirely black; the mandible lacks a ventral tooth basally; the head and T2 disc have separated punctures; the forewing has its veins encompassing the basal 0.7 × of the wing; the T1 shape is sub-sessile; the T2 fringe is composed of simple setae; and the paramere is virtually straight, subcylindrical, and having evenly distributed short setae. Body length 
<quantity id="4CA09B537C11CD24268D9E22FDEFF931" box="[429,525,1662,1687]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="124" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
